00:47:07.700 --> 00:47:10.960
Now, I've met with a number of you today
and I understand that the marketing

00:47:10.960 --> 00:47:15.440
budgets of you vary in this audience
from a zero dollar marketing budget

00:47:15.440 --> 00:47:17.380
to maybe millions of dollars.

00:47:17.990 --> 00:47:21.720
And my goal here is to share with you
various channels that hopefully there's a

00:47:21.740 --> 00:47:25.790
tidbit of information and tips that will
help all of you here in this audience,

00:47:25.880 --> 00:47:27.970
depending upon your budget.

00:47:28.550 --> 00:47:30.460
So I've broken it down into two buckets.

00:47:30.490 --> 00:47:33.840
Owned channels are more or
less free and paid channels are

00:47:33.840 --> 00:47:36.000
obviously those you have to pay.

00:47:36.130 --> 00:47:38.160
So let's jump in to the
owned channels first,

00:47:38.160 --> 00:47:39.240
and we'll start with social media.

00:47:41.140 --> 00:47:43.750
Social media is one of the most
effective channels that you

00:47:43.750 --> 00:47:45.330
can use to market your app.

00:47:45.400 --> 00:47:48.370
I know you know this,
but it's important that you

00:47:48.570 --> 00:47:51.990
plan that social media strategy
from the very beginning.

00:47:52.100 --> 00:47:56.580
How can you integrate social
media into your game experience?

00:47:56.630 --> 00:47:58.980
As Alex said earlier,
ShareSheet is one great

00:47:58.980 --> 00:48:00.120
way of doing that.

00:48:00.120 --> 00:48:03.290
It's very simple to
share maybe high scores,

00:48:03.490 --> 00:48:07.490
milestones,
and achievements through ShareSheet.

00:48:08.660 --> 00:48:10.430
But I also want you to think about
how you can leverage social media

00:48:10.430 --> 00:48:12.860
to maybe supplement your game.

00:48:12.920 --> 00:48:16.360
You know, instead of using social media
just as a broadcast mechanism,

00:48:16.420 --> 00:48:19.500
how can you use it to bring
content back into your game?

00:48:19.670 --> 00:48:23.000
See where your friends are at
certain levels or things like that.

00:48:23.060 --> 00:48:25.680
Now, while this isn't a game example,
it is a great example,

00:48:25.680 --> 00:48:27.340
and this is with RunKeeper.

00:48:27.390 --> 00:48:31.630
RunKeeper actually leverages social
media where you can have your friends

00:48:31.640 --> 00:48:36.090
and family motivate you and cheer you
on for a run through social media.

00:48:36.260 --> 00:48:39.980
So it's a different way to look at
social media and how to augment your app.

00:48:41.140 --> 00:48:43.470
But beyond that,
you need to think about how you're

00:48:43.470 --> 00:48:47.090
going to build your brand presence
on social media and what is your

00:48:47.090 --> 00:48:48.970
content strategy going to be.

00:48:49.020 --> 00:48:51.300
So there's three things
I want to leave you with.

00:48:51.500 --> 00:48:55.720
The first, remember that when you
are posting content,

00:48:55.720 --> 00:48:58.870
those posts are going to be nestled
amongst the posts of your customers,

00:48:58.990 --> 00:49:00.350
friends, and family.

00:49:00.500 --> 00:49:01.920
So be engaging.

00:49:01.930 --> 00:49:03.460
Be conversational.

00:49:03.480 --> 00:49:05.890
Don't continually just sell, sell,
sell all the time.

00:49:06.140 --> 00:49:08.740
Get them to engage with your content.

00:49:09.590 --> 00:49:12.620
and think about how you can
get them to arrest the thumb.

00:49:12.670 --> 00:49:15.360
We all flip through our
news feeds very quickly.

00:49:15.410 --> 00:49:19.990
And what gets us to stop is that
compelling image or that compelling copy.

00:49:20.070 --> 00:49:22.680
And if it gets you to somebody
to stop and to read it,

00:49:22.740 --> 00:49:26.400
your next step is to hopefully
get them to engage and share it.

00:49:26.450 --> 00:49:28.690
Which takes me to my third point.

00:49:28.750 --> 00:49:30.700
People are what they share.

00:49:30.770 --> 00:49:32.300
They share what inspires them.

00:49:32.300 --> 00:49:35.090
They share what is aspirational to them.

00:49:35.160 --> 00:49:38.450
So think about that copy that
addresses both of those things,

00:49:38.630 --> 00:49:41.300
inspiration and aspiration.

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:43.890
So that's social media.

00:49:44.170 --> 00:49:46.700
Let's talk about email briefly.

00:49:46.740 --> 00:49:51.300
Email is likely your first
opportunity to talk to a customer

00:49:51.510 --> 00:49:53.240
outside of the App Store.

00:49:53.360 --> 00:49:56.210
So that first contact
is really important.

00:49:56.380 --> 00:50:00.090
Think about how you can be engaging and
useful so that they don't immediately

00:50:00.220 --> 00:50:01.720
put you into their spam folder.

00:50:01.940 --> 00:50:04.650
You want to use email
throughout the lifecycle of

00:50:04.650 --> 00:50:06.170
your customer with your game.

00:50:06.310 --> 00:50:10.890
So make sure that content is-- it
jumps out and is engaging to them.

00:50:11.850 --> 00:50:15.200
and optimize your emails for the
devices it's being viewed on.

00:50:15.330 --> 00:50:18.700
You need to consider the
image sizes that you're using,

00:50:18.810 --> 00:50:22.080
the font types,
and the font sizes so that they're

00:50:22.080 --> 00:50:24.810
both viewable on both iPhone and iPad.

00:50:25.170 --> 00:50:26.900
Which brings me to my third point.

00:50:26.970 --> 00:50:29.260
You know your customer that
you're talking to here is an

00:50:29.260 --> 00:50:31.260
iPhone or an iPad customer.

00:50:31.260 --> 00:50:33.280
So target those communications to them.

00:50:33.370 --> 00:50:35.590
Talk to them directly and make
them feel special like they're

00:50:35.640 --> 00:50:36.700
a part of your experience.

00:50:39.720 --> 00:50:44.200
Another thing to remember is to
make your entire image clickable.

00:50:44.300 --> 00:50:46.400
When you're providing
an image in your email,

00:50:46.510 --> 00:50:48.800
customers know that as a call
to action and they just want

00:50:48.800 --> 00:50:49.670
to be able to tap anywhere.

00:50:49.910 --> 00:50:53.750
So don't make them sort of target and
find that really small call to action.

00:50:53.840 --> 00:50:55.910
Allow them to click anywhere.

00:50:57.080 --> 00:51:01.890
Next, use email as a way to test
your marketing strategies.

00:51:01.890 --> 00:51:04.420
And one great way to do that
is test your subject line.

00:51:04.420 --> 00:51:08.810
So as you're doing an email blast,
segment your audience into two

00:51:09.190 --> 00:51:13.800
groups and do A/B testing and see
how the results affect open rate.

00:51:13.940 --> 00:51:16.930
Take those learnings and apply
them to your next email and your

00:51:16.930 --> 00:51:20.000
next email and you're going to
get smarter and you're going to

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:22.210
continue to drive great engagement.

00:51:23.620 --> 00:51:26.040
You want to be useful in your content?

00:51:26.050 --> 00:51:28.660
So you don't, again,
you don't always need to be selling.

00:51:28.690 --> 00:51:31.660
Maybe provide them tips and tricks
on how to get to that next level or

00:51:32.030 --> 00:51:35.220
give them an insight of what the,
you know, level 47 is going to be,

00:51:35.220 --> 00:51:36.150
whatever that's going to be.

00:51:36.350 --> 00:51:38.180
Get them to engage with your app again.

00:51:38.180 --> 00:51:41.160
And then also use email to
support that social media

00:51:41.230 --> 00:51:43.510
strategy we talked about earlier.

00:51:43.530 --> 00:51:47.060
Get them to follow you on the
popular social media networks.

00:51:49.270 --> 00:51:49.760
So that's email.

00:51:49.760 --> 00:51:52.660
So now some tips for your website.

00:51:52.660 --> 00:51:58.600
Back at iOS 6, we launched a technology
called Smart App Banners.

00:51:58.600 --> 00:52:02.660
With Smart App Banners,
all you need to do is enter one

00:52:02.660 --> 00:52:04.460
line of code onto your website.

00:52:04.460 --> 00:52:07.230
And with that,
your website will be able to

00:52:07.230 --> 00:52:10.940
detect if a customer is coming
to you from an iOS device.

00:52:10.980 --> 00:52:13.360
And when that happens,
a banner is presented

00:52:13.360 --> 00:52:14.690
at the top of your page.

00:52:15.440 --> 00:52:18.980
And it's smart because it knows,
in this case, whether or not I have

00:52:18.980 --> 00:52:20.600
Diamond Dash installed on my device.

00:52:20.700 --> 00:52:24.100
If I don't, the call to action says View.

00:52:24.100 --> 00:52:26.200
And when I tap on View,
I'm taken into the

00:52:26.240 --> 00:52:27.910
App Store to download the app.

00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:30.510
But if I do have the
app installed already,

00:52:30.520 --> 00:52:31.470
it says Open.

00:52:31.480 --> 00:52:33.320
And I have the ability
to just tap on that,

00:52:33.320 --> 00:52:35.320
and then it launches the game directly.

00:52:37.880 --> 00:52:41.100
It's important to optimize
your website for mobile.

00:52:41.100 --> 00:52:43.020
Very similar to what I said with email.

00:52:43.150 --> 00:52:46.000
Think about your image size and
your font type and your font sizes

00:52:46.000 --> 00:52:50.980
so that you can engage with it on a
smaller form factor like the iPhone.

00:52:52.500 --> 00:52:55.090
and provide multiple install points.

00:52:55.090 --> 00:52:57.430
Once the customer begins
scrolling through your page and

00:52:57.440 --> 00:53:00.270
they lose that smart app banner,
provide the App Store badge

00:53:00.280 --> 00:53:02.640
on there so they can click
on it and download your game.

00:53:02.640 --> 00:53:05.420
Again,
support that social media strategy.

00:53:05.420 --> 00:53:09.480
Allow your customers to follow you on
Facebook and Twitter or other networks.

00:53:09.480 --> 00:53:14.390
And then finally,
provide a link to customer care or

00:53:14.390 --> 00:53:19.510
an FAQ so that you can address your
customers' problems directly rather than

00:53:19.510 --> 00:53:24.520
them leaving you negative feedback on
the App Store and affecting your ratings.

00:53:25.850 --> 00:53:30.100
Now the next channel I want to talk
about briefly is cross promotion.

00:53:30.150 --> 00:53:34.200
Many of you in the audience have
multiple apps on the App Store.

00:53:34.200 --> 00:53:37.840
And I've seen some good and not so good
ways that you can cross promote apps.

00:53:37.840 --> 00:53:40.760
But the thing to remember is to be
thoughtful to your customers that

00:53:41.050 --> 00:53:44.110
you've already worked so hard to
acquire and don't be too intrusive

00:53:44.110 --> 00:53:46.260
when you're doing that cross marketing.

00:53:46.260 --> 00:53:48.800
So I'm going to provide
you three examples here of

00:53:48.800 --> 00:53:51.730
what I think is thoughtful,
good cross marketing.

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:54.260
The first is the More Apps menu.

00:53:54.260 --> 00:53:56.940
And with Cut the Rope,
they've provided this little

00:53:57.050 --> 00:53:58.700
window shade pole at the very top.

00:53:58.800 --> 00:54:02.370
And by pulling down on it,
it's interactive, it supports gravity,

00:54:02.380 --> 00:54:04.900
what have you,
but you can slip through the other

00:54:04.900 --> 00:54:07.000
games that ZeptoLabs provides.

00:54:07.950 --> 00:54:09.480
Another example are tickers.

00:54:09.580 --> 00:54:11.200
These are not intrusive.

00:54:11.200 --> 00:54:13.600
So here I am looking
at the Sims Free Play,

00:54:13.770 --> 00:54:17.960
and the streaming ticker at the
bottom is talking about FIFA 14.

00:54:17.960 --> 00:54:20.360
It's being thoughtful,
it's talking about the

00:54:20.360 --> 00:54:21.800
benefits of FIFA 14.

00:54:22.540 --> 00:54:25.640
And if I'm interested,
I simply tap on it, and I'm taken to the

00:54:25.720 --> 00:54:27.280
App Store to download it.

00:54:30.020 --> 00:54:31.500
And then the third example is
what we call interactive creative.

00:54:31.610 --> 00:54:34.180
What the impossible line has done
here is you can take these bubbles

00:54:34.280 --> 00:54:36.530
from the upper right-hand corner,
pull them down,

00:54:36.530 --> 00:54:39.350
you can bounce them off one another,
you can interact with it,

00:54:39.560 --> 00:54:43.120
but by tapping on it,
it pops the bubble and then it takes you

00:54:43.120 --> 00:54:45.080
into the App Store via a store sheet.

00:54:45.910 --> 00:54:49.480
And that's my last point I want to
emphasize here is to use store sheet.

00:54:49.630 --> 00:54:52.890
By using store sheet,
the customer could engage and

00:54:52.890 --> 00:54:56.630
buy this game and then once
that transaction is complete,

00:54:56.730 --> 00:54:59.690
they're taken right back into the
game where they were previously

00:54:59.690 --> 00:55:02.750
and you haven't lost that,
their spot in the game.

00:55:03.680 --> 00:55:05.310
Next I want to talk about PR.

00:55:05.580 --> 00:55:09.800
I want to remind you that PR does
not stand for press release.

00:55:09.940 --> 00:55:14.500
Gone are the days where a press release
makes a comprehensive PR campaign.

00:55:14.500 --> 00:55:17.290
It stands for public
relations and it takes work.

00:55:17.510 --> 00:55:18.440
It doesn't cost you anything.

00:55:18.500 --> 00:55:20.880
It just takes your energy and
effort to go out there and

00:55:20.880 --> 00:55:22.500
find the influencers out there.

00:55:22.500 --> 00:55:26.480
And that's where the promo
codes come into play.

00:55:26.630 --> 00:55:29.740
Those 100 promo codes you can pull
out of iTunes Connect shouldn't

00:55:29.740 --> 00:55:32.310
be used for your brother,
your sister, your mom, or your dad.

00:55:32.310 --> 00:55:35.500
Give it to the influencers out there,
those people that can

00:55:35.500 --> 00:55:36.560
write about your app.

00:55:36.560 --> 00:55:39.190
And please, embargo them.

00:55:39.190 --> 00:55:43.580
Don't allow them to write about your game
until your app is live on the App Store.

00:55:43.580 --> 00:55:46.540
It really does you very little
good for them to write about you,

00:55:46.540 --> 00:55:48.770
for when the audience
is reading that article,

00:55:48.770 --> 00:55:49.830
they can't act on it.

00:55:49.830 --> 00:55:51.570
There's nothing for them to do.

00:55:51.820 --> 00:55:54.880
So wait for them to write about
you until your app is live on the

00:55:54.880 --> 00:55:58.100
store and drive as much PR in a
short amount of time as you can.

00:55:59.800 --> 00:56:02.580
Beyond launch,
you want to find an advocate.

00:56:02.660 --> 00:56:05.580
You want to find somebody that can
continue to talk about your app.

00:56:05.760 --> 00:56:08.870
I see some great examples with
racing games where they've gotten

00:56:08.870 --> 00:56:11.910
race car drivers to continually talk
about it and show their levels as

00:56:11.910 --> 00:56:13.690
they're progressing through games.

00:56:13.910 --> 00:56:18.250
Really consider finding an advocate that
can continue to talk about your game.

00:56:18.510 --> 00:56:20.810
Now,
if you do want to write a press release,

00:56:20.810 --> 00:56:23.730
make sure you can support
your claims that you make.

00:56:23.820 --> 00:56:26.550
And then finally,
please send them to us ahead

00:56:26.550 --> 00:56:28.120
of time for our review.

00:56:28.120 --> 00:56:31.240
You can send them to us at
pressreleasesatapple.com and our

00:56:31.240 --> 00:56:35.300
PR team will look at them and give you
any feedback within five business days.

00:56:36.460 --> 00:56:39.010
So the last owned channel I want
to talk about are trailers.

00:56:39.010 --> 00:56:42.630
And I love the trailers I'm
seeing from the audience like you,

00:56:42.630 --> 00:56:43.860
game developers.

00:56:43.860 --> 00:56:48.330
The production value of trailers nowadays
have really gone to the next step.

00:56:48.410 --> 00:56:50.860
But I want to give you a few
tips and tricks of things that

00:56:51.030 --> 00:56:52.520
we like to see in trailers.

00:56:53.660 --> 00:56:56.960
And the first thing is that you
need to grab somebody's attention.

00:56:56.960 --> 00:56:59.550
And with a trailer,
we have found that you have about six

00:56:59.760 --> 00:57:03.410
seconds to grab somebody's attention
of whether or not they want to continue

00:57:03.410 --> 00:57:05.460
to watch what your game is about.

00:57:06.630 --> 00:57:09.330
But that being said,
they do have a limited attention span.

00:57:09.330 --> 00:57:12.120
So keep your trailer to
within 30 to 60 seconds.

00:57:14.030 --> 00:57:16.290
As I said earlier,
I know you work really hard

00:57:16.380 --> 00:57:18.290
to make your game look great.

00:57:18.290 --> 00:57:24.000
So use professional capturing tools to
capture digitally your gaming experience.

00:57:24.030 --> 00:57:27.140
Don't have your friend look over you with
a camera and record you playing with it.

00:57:27.190 --> 00:57:29.080
Use these digital capturing systems.

00:57:29.080 --> 00:57:32.560
And then support your trailer
with a great soundtrack.

00:57:33.720 --> 00:57:36.080
You're going to want to provide
a clear call to action because in

00:57:36.080 --> 00:57:39.360
many cases those trailers aren't,
you can't click with them.

00:57:39.560 --> 00:57:41.860
So make sure you provide
the App Store badge,

00:57:41.870 --> 00:57:44.490
a vanity URL,
whatever that may be to get them to go

00:57:44.490 --> 00:57:46.870
into the App Store to download your app.

00:57:50.200 --> 00:57:51.080
And the last point I want to
make about trailers is to ensure

00:57:51.080 --> 00:57:52.950
that it's globally appropriate.

00:57:53.390 --> 00:57:55.200
And there's two aspects to this.

00:57:55.220 --> 00:57:56.140
The first is price.

00:57:56.140 --> 00:58:00.700
So if your app or your
game is a paid-for app,

00:58:00.950 --> 00:58:04.460
when you talk about it in one currency,
that doesn't really translate to

00:58:04.460 --> 00:58:06.200
other currencies around the globe.

00:58:06.640 --> 00:58:08.280
You know,
somebody in Japan or China might not know

00:58:08.280 --> 00:58:10.200
what the conversion rate is for a euro,
for example.

00:58:10.200 --> 00:58:13.710
Additionally, by talking about your
specific price point,

00:58:13.800 --> 00:58:17.200
it doesn't give you the opportunity
to do price promotions as well.

00:58:17.310 --> 00:58:20.250
So we really just encourage
you to leave the price out of

00:58:20.250 --> 00:58:21.990
it unless your game is free.

00:58:22.550 --> 00:58:26.640
The other aspect to being globally
appropriate is the content itself.

00:58:26.880 --> 00:58:31.630
And the level at which people are
offended by maybe violence or other

00:58:31.630 --> 00:58:33.660
types of content varies around the globe.

00:58:33.660 --> 00:58:36.930
So be sure that you err on the side
of caution so that people will want

00:58:37.120 --> 00:58:39.260
to continue to watch these trailers.

00:58:39.260 --> 00:58:43.050
So the example I have here is from
EA of their trailer for FIFA 14.

00:58:43.050 --> 00:58:46.280
And many of you may have seen this,
but those that haven't,

00:58:46.280 --> 00:58:49.420
they've done a great job of
really building a great trailer

00:58:49.420 --> 00:58:51.570
using many of these tactics here.

00:59:36.170 --> 00:59:39.850
So I'll conclude by talking
about two paid channels.

00:59:39.850 --> 00:59:41.980
And the first is mobile ads.

00:59:42.010 --> 00:59:45.450
I won't go too deep into here because
I touched on it with iAd earlier,

00:59:45.640 --> 00:59:49.880
but one of the benefits of mobile ads
obviously is that through mobile ads,

00:59:49.880 --> 00:59:52.600
it's the fewest taps
away from an install.

00:59:52.640 --> 00:59:55.760
As you're engaging with a
game or an app or a website,

00:59:55.760 --> 00:59:59.850
when you see those banner ads,
it's one tap and you're downloading

00:59:59.850 --> 01:00:01.820
the content within the store.

01:00:02.040 --> 01:00:05.500
But you can also use mobile ads
not only for user acquisition,

01:00:05.500 --> 01:00:06.970
but also to help build your brand.

01:00:06.990 --> 01:00:08.250
We encourage you to do both.

01:00:08.270 --> 01:00:11.410
And also the benefit primarily
around that you can target

01:00:11.410 --> 01:00:14.530
your campaigns by device,
by demographic, by interest,

01:00:14.600 --> 01:00:16.120
whatever that might be.

01:00:18.800 --> 01:00:22.240
Now one tip I want to provide you
though is your creative direction.

01:00:22.270 --> 01:00:25.600
You can't create a single piece
of creative for all the channels

01:00:25.600 --> 01:00:26.800
that you're marketing through.

01:00:26.920 --> 01:00:31.000
So make sure that you create custom
creative dependent upon that channel.

01:00:31.480 --> 01:00:33.120
We have heard from
developers on Facebook,

01:00:33.170 --> 01:00:35.150
for example,
it's better to use live action photos

01:00:35.150 --> 01:00:36.470
like you might see here for Hay Day.

01:00:36.770 --> 01:00:40.500
That actually drives higher
engagement for developers.

01:00:41.460 --> 01:00:43.500
But it's also important that you test.

01:00:43.500 --> 01:00:46.860
So I know some developers that
will create upwards of 50 pieces

01:00:46.860 --> 01:00:48.510
of creative for one campaign.

01:00:48.700 --> 01:00:53.010
They'll very quickly learn what works
best and what doesn't and continue to

01:00:53.010 --> 01:00:55.550
invest in that creative that does work.

01:00:56.820 --> 01:01:00.600
And now my last point and my last channel
I want to share with you is television.

01:01:00.730 --> 01:01:03.460
I understand this might be out
of the budget of many of you,

01:01:03.460 --> 01:01:07.390
but I'm seeing some great
TV campaigns around the globe,

01:01:07.460 --> 01:01:09.610
a lot of them here in Europe as well.

01:01:11.060 --> 01:01:13.350
And what makes television
work so well is the fact that

01:01:13.480 --> 01:01:16.220
while people are watching TV,
their devices are at hand.

01:01:16.220 --> 01:01:19.910
Either their iPhone is in their pocket,
their iPad is on their lap,

01:01:19.990 --> 01:01:23.100
and if the television
commercial is engaging enough,

01:01:23.330 --> 01:01:27.730
you will see them convert and you'll
actually see results in near real time.

01:01:28.280 --> 01:01:31.010
But it's important that you share
the magic moments of your game

01:01:31.300 --> 01:01:34.260
to make sure that it's engaging
and you get people to convert.

01:01:34.820 --> 01:01:37.140
You want to support it
with a strong voiceover,

01:01:37.140 --> 01:01:40.020
maybe talking about the key features,
the devices.

01:01:41.300 --> 01:01:44.080
But of course, you're going to want to
have a clear call to action.

01:01:45.520 --> 01:01:50.190
One way to create a clear call to
action is by having a strong end frame.

01:01:50.190 --> 01:01:53.990
By that strong end frame,
what I mean is that the last three

01:01:54.090 --> 01:01:57.580
or four seconds of a TV spot,
make sure you have the App Store badge,

01:01:57.690 --> 01:01:59.320
but use your vanity URL.

01:01:59.340 --> 01:02:01.450
I should have mentioned this earlier.

01:02:01.450 --> 01:02:05.300
Your vanity URL is something that
every one of you in this audience have.

01:02:05.380 --> 01:02:10.320
You have your own appstore.com URL,
which would be appstore.com slash

01:02:10.320 --> 01:02:14.460
your app name or appstore.com
slash your developer name.

01:02:15.080 --> 01:02:18.230
And by using that in offline media,
such as TV or print or

01:02:18.230 --> 01:02:21.850
billboard or what have you,
it's a URL that your customers could

01:02:21.850 --> 01:02:26.210
easily remember and then go convert
and get them to activate against.

01:02:27.700 --> 01:02:31.330
So the TV spot I'm going to
share with you is from Wooga

01:02:31.710 --> 01:02:35.160
for their new Jelly Splash game,
or for the Jelly Splash game.

01:02:35.460 --> 01:02:37.790
And they've done a great job of
capturing all these tips here

01:02:37.940 --> 01:02:39.430
to produce a really great spot.

01:02:39.440 --> 01:02:41.600
Plus they've added a
little bit of humor to it,

01:02:41.610 --> 01:02:43.980
which I think helps
drive engagement as well.

01:02:59.400 --> 01:03:00.000
Jelly Splash.

01:03:00.000 --> 01:03:01.860
The most addictive puzzle game ever.

01:03:01.860 --> 01:03:03.380
Search Jelly Splash now.

01:03:03.380 --> 01:03:05.240
The hit game played by millions.

01:03:05.240 --> 01:03:07.700
Download for free on iPhone and iPad.

01:03:07.700 --> 01:03:09.460
Play Jelly Splash today.

01:03:11.410 --> 01:03:14.200
So great example of the badge usage,
great example of the vanity

01:03:14.200 --> 01:03:17.570
URL I mentioned earlier,
all in all a great spot.

01:03:18.100 --> 01:03:21.700
So I want to leave with
you with an email address.

01:03:21.700 --> 01:03:25.840
This is appstoremarketing@apple.com.

01:03:25.940 --> 01:03:29.660
This gives you direct access
to our global marketing team.

01:03:29.760 --> 01:03:32.340
If you have any questions
about your marketing campaigns,

01:03:32.340 --> 01:03:35.360
your strategies, if you want to send us
your assets for review,

01:03:35.360 --> 01:03:37.030
we would love to take a look at it.

01:03:37.280 --> 01:03:39.090
We will respond to you
within five business days.

01:03:39.250 --> 01:03:42.080
So with that, I want to thank you,
and I'm going to hand it

01:03:42.080 --> 01:03:45.320
over to Shannon Bruce to
talk about iTunes Connect.

01:03:49.010 --> 01:03:53.100
My name is Shannon Bruce and I work
on the App Store operations team.

01:03:53.100 --> 01:03:56.880
You've been hearing some great tips
on choosing the right business model

01:03:56.880 --> 01:03:58.820
and how to best market your app.

01:03:58.820 --> 01:04:02.290
And I'm going to talk some more
about how you can execute on some of

01:04:02.290 --> 01:04:04.550
these things through iTunes Connect.

01:04:04.950 --> 01:04:07.980
I know that all of you have at
least one app on the App Store,

01:04:07.990 --> 01:04:11.000
so you should be very
familiar with iTunes Connect.

01:04:11.000 --> 01:04:13.880
And it is the gateway to the App Store.

01:04:13.980 --> 01:04:17.740
It's the website you use to
create and manage your apps,

01:04:17.890 --> 01:04:23.580
check your payments and sales reports,
request your promo codes, and much more.

01:04:23.750 --> 01:04:26.540
I'm going to cover three
major topics today.

01:04:26.600 --> 01:04:30.900
First, I'll go over some recently
launched and valuable features.

01:04:31.060 --> 01:04:33.700
Second,
I'll talk about how you can execute

01:04:33.700 --> 01:04:36.380
on your plans to localize your app.

01:04:36.380 --> 01:04:38.580
And finally,
I'll leave you with some tips

01:04:38.580 --> 01:04:42.700
and tricks to help manage your
business more effectively.

01:04:42.700 --> 01:04:46.160
Let's start with our first feature,
promo codes.

01:04:46.680 --> 01:04:51.910
We provide you with 100 promo codes
for your use and they're set up

01:04:52.190 --> 01:04:55.670
so that you can request them as
you need them in any denomination.

01:04:57.240 --> 01:05:00.440
As Steve mentioned,
we encourage you to reserve these

01:05:00.440 --> 01:05:04.840
codes for your media representatives
and influencers who can try out

01:05:04.840 --> 01:05:08.740
your app before it's available
to the general public and write

01:05:08.740 --> 01:05:11.210
about it to help you promote it.

01:05:11.480 --> 01:05:14.760
Up until recently,
you were only able to request promo

01:05:14.760 --> 01:05:19.130
codes in the ready for sale state,
but I'm happy to announce that you

01:05:19.230 --> 01:05:24.000
can now request promo codes in the
pending developer release state as well.

01:05:24.110 --> 01:05:28.660
This is really exciting because it
allows you to request promo codes for

01:05:28.660 --> 01:05:33.370
your app updates in addition to your
first version of the app so you can

01:05:33.370 --> 01:05:35.970
promote your new features as well.

01:05:36.650 --> 01:05:39.750
The next feature I want to
talk about is app transfer.

01:05:39.930 --> 01:05:43.880
This is a very exciting launch
for us this year at WWDC,

01:05:43.930 --> 01:05:46.680
as it was a highly
requested feature by you.

01:05:46.740 --> 01:05:50.520
And it's the ability to transfer
the ownership of an app from one

01:05:50.520 --> 01:05:52.980
developer account to another.

01:05:53.520 --> 01:05:56.820
And what are some of the reasons
you might use App Transfer?

01:05:56.850 --> 01:05:59.600
The App Store has been in
business for five years now,

01:05:59.620 --> 01:06:02.680
and many of you have
seen phenomenal success.

01:06:02.700 --> 01:06:07.020
You may have had the opportunity to
sell your app to another developer,

01:06:07.020 --> 01:06:11.190
or you may have acquired a great
app from another developer.

01:06:11.500 --> 01:06:15.240
Or maybe you've registered
multiple accounts with Apple and

01:06:15.240 --> 01:06:19.400
would like to consolidate those
accounts to be managed as one.

01:06:19.500 --> 01:06:24.450
If you're in any of these situations,
App Transfer is a great solution for you.

01:06:24.890 --> 01:06:26.940
And what are the benefits?

01:06:26.960 --> 01:06:30.240
One of the greatest things about app
transfer is that it is completely

01:06:30.240 --> 01:06:32.900
seamless to your customers.

01:06:33.090 --> 01:06:37.800
What that means is that customers can
continue to use the app and new customers

01:06:37.800 --> 01:06:42.910
can continue to purchase the app while
the transfer process is happening.

01:06:43.140 --> 01:06:45.800
And you get to retain all
of your chart placement,

01:06:45.940 --> 01:06:49.860
your customer ratings and reviews,
and the ability to update

01:06:49.860 --> 01:06:52.720
the app for your customers.

01:06:53.080 --> 01:06:57.810
And there are really just very minimal
visible changes to the app on the store.

01:06:58.050 --> 01:07:02.080
The only thing that changes on
the App Store is the seller name.

01:07:03.060 --> 01:07:06.480
So let's walk through a flow to
show you what this looks like.

01:07:06.510 --> 01:07:10.400
First, as the current owner,
you'll log into iTunes Connect,

01:07:10.510 --> 01:07:15.220
select the app you wish to transfer,
and enter in the new owner information.

01:07:15.220 --> 01:07:21.010
That's the Apple ID of the team agent
and the team ID of the new owner.

01:07:21.020 --> 01:07:26.180
Then Apple will draw up a contract
agreement between you and the new owner,

01:07:26.430 --> 01:07:32.000
and the app will move into a
substate called Pending App Transfer.

01:07:32.000 --> 01:07:34.700
If your app is ready
for sale at this time,

01:07:34.700 --> 01:07:37.110
it remains on the store,
as all of this is

01:07:37.110 --> 01:07:39.410
happening on the back end.

01:07:40.360 --> 01:07:43.480
At the same time,
the new owner will receive an email

01:07:43.480 --> 01:07:47.000
letting them know that a transfer
is waiting their acceptance.

01:07:47.050 --> 01:07:51.020
They'll log into iTunes Connect and
they'll be required to enter

01:07:51.020 --> 01:07:53.540
in some new app metadata.

01:07:53.610 --> 01:07:56.560
I'll go into detail about
what this is in a minute.

01:07:56.620 --> 01:08:00.480
They will also sign the same
contract agreement and once both

01:08:00.910 --> 01:08:05.120
developers have signed the contract,
the app moves into processing

01:08:05.260 --> 01:08:09.480
app transfer where it's moving
from one account to the next.

01:08:10.710 --> 01:08:12.980
There are some rules
regarding app transfer,

01:08:12.980 --> 01:08:15.040
and I want to go over just a
few of them that you should know

01:08:15.040 --> 01:08:17.700
about before transferring an app.

01:08:18.260 --> 01:08:23.100
You'll want to make sure you've agreed
to any available contract amendments.

01:08:23.360 --> 01:08:25.860
From time to time,
Apple updates the terms of

01:08:25.860 --> 01:08:29.520
the program license agreement
or the paid apps contract.

01:08:29.580 --> 01:08:32.280
And we just want to make sure
that you've agreed to these

01:08:32.280 --> 01:08:34.210
terms before transferring an app.

01:08:35.730 --> 01:08:39.780
You also need to have at least
one approved version for your app,

01:08:39.850 --> 01:08:43.760
and you won't be able to transfer
an app that is currently in review.

01:08:43.880 --> 01:08:47.180
This includes in-app
purchase reviews as well.

01:08:48.700 --> 01:08:51.090
So as the current owner,
what are some things you should have

01:08:51.140 --> 01:08:54.350
ready before initiating a transfer?

01:08:54.840 --> 01:08:57.300
You'll need to collect
the new owner information,

01:08:57.300 --> 01:09:00.040
that is the Apple ID of the team agent.

01:09:00.100 --> 01:09:03.160
This isn't their password,
just the username they use

01:09:03.190 --> 01:09:05.560
to log into iTunes Connect.

01:09:05.560 --> 01:09:06.890
And the team ID.

01:09:06.890 --> 01:09:10.760
The team ID is a unique identifier
for your developer account,

01:09:10.760 --> 01:09:13.710
and you can find this
ID in the member center.

01:09:15.500 --> 01:09:17.500
We also encourage you to
back up your app history.

01:09:17.500 --> 01:09:21.030
Once the app is transferred,
it's completely gone out of

01:09:21.030 --> 01:09:23.830
your iTunes Connect account,
so you won't have access

01:09:23.830 --> 01:09:25.380
to any of its current data.

01:09:25.380 --> 01:09:28.340
So if you want to request a
catalog report or just have this

01:09:28.340 --> 01:09:31.500
information for your own records,
you should do this before

01:09:31.500 --> 01:09:33.150
initiating the transfer.

01:09:34.200 --> 01:09:38.230
And you'll need to arrange the actual
transfer of the source code and

01:09:38.230 --> 01:09:40.640
binary of the app with the new owner.

01:09:41.360 --> 01:09:44.480
Because the only thing that the
transfer process does is transfer

01:09:44.480 --> 01:09:44.480
the data to the new owner.

01:09:45.240 --> 01:09:48.250
So then once the transfer
has been initiated,

01:09:48.250 --> 01:09:50.720
the app is under metadata lockdown.

01:09:50.720 --> 01:09:54.810
What this means is that you can
still make changes to the pricing

01:09:54.810 --> 01:09:58.500
and availability of the app,
but you will be locked out of

01:09:58.500 --> 01:10:00.900
making changes to anything else.

01:10:02.510 --> 01:10:07.380
And the recipient has 60 days
in order to accept the transfer.

01:10:07.380 --> 01:10:10.200
If they do not accept
within the 60-day period,

01:10:10.210 --> 01:10:13.400
it will automatically be canceled.

01:10:13.460 --> 01:10:16.120
So then as the new owner,
what are some things you should have

01:10:16.120 --> 01:10:18.800
ready before accepting an app transfer?

01:10:18.810 --> 01:10:22.440
You'll want to have that new app
metadata that I mentioned earlier.

01:10:22.490 --> 01:10:24.480
Since the ownership of
the app is changing,

01:10:24.600 --> 01:10:28.900
we're under the assumption that the
contact information is changing as well.

01:10:28.900 --> 01:10:33.700
So we require that you enter in the
support URL and marketing URL for

01:10:33.700 --> 01:10:37.600
your app so that we can ensure that
customers are directed to the correct

01:10:37.770 --> 01:10:40.770
place as the ownership changes.

01:10:41.900 --> 01:10:45.800
This includes your app review
contact information as well.

01:10:45.840 --> 01:10:49.280
This information is important so
that if any questions or issues

01:10:49.280 --> 01:10:54.790
arise during the review of your app,
we have a way of contacting you.

01:10:56.200 --> 01:10:59.270
And if the app contains encryption,
the previous owner may have supplied

01:10:59.280 --> 01:11:02.410
export compliance documentation
and you'll want to have this

01:11:02.410 --> 01:11:04.280
documentation ready as well.

01:11:04.340 --> 01:11:08.060
Many of you who acquire an app like
to submit an update in order to

01:11:08.060 --> 01:11:11.880
make any changes to the branding
information within the app.

01:11:11.940 --> 01:11:16.170
And we encourage you to have this
update ready so that you can submit it

01:11:16.360 --> 01:11:18.700
as soon as the transfer is complete.

01:11:18.770 --> 01:11:22.100
Then when the app moves into the
processing app transfer state,

01:11:22.170 --> 01:11:28.400
the transfer has begun and the pricing is
locked down in addition to the metadata.

01:11:28.470 --> 01:11:31.250
This should only take about 30 minutes,
so you shouldn't be

01:11:31.350 --> 01:11:33.980
locked out for too long,
but the transfer cannot

01:11:33.980 --> 01:11:35.620
be canceled at this time.

01:11:35.680 --> 01:11:40.700
It's literally when the app is moving
from the current owner to the new owner.

01:11:41.790 --> 01:11:44.210
So just to show you what this
looks like on the App Store,

01:11:44.390 --> 01:11:47.710
Angry Birds was one of our
first apps to be transferred.

01:11:47.710 --> 01:11:51.070
And you can see that the only thing
that changes on the App Store is the

01:11:51.070 --> 01:11:55.160
seller name from Chilingo to Rovio.

01:11:55.280 --> 01:11:57.440
So that's app transfer.

01:11:58.510 --> 01:12:02.040
The next feature I want to
cover is alternate price tiers.

01:12:02.160 --> 01:12:05.900
We recently introduced some
additional tiers for your use.

01:12:05.980 --> 01:12:10.840
These tiers are available for
developers globally who wish to vary

01:12:10.840 --> 01:12:12.910
pricing in different currencies.

01:12:12.950 --> 01:12:16.400
And they just give you a little
more flexibility to price your app

01:12:16.410 --> 01:12:18.550
thoughtfully and competitively.

01:12:19.240 --> 01:12:22.300
There are five additional
tiers for your use.

01:12:22.350 --> 01:12:27.220
They are completely market optimized,
which means that they're culturally

01:12:27.220 --> 01:12:31.340
relevant and consumer friendly to
the regions using those currencies.

01:12:31.340 --> 01:12:36.330
And there are no restrictions,
meaning you can choose these for any

01:12:36.330 --> 01:12:39.080
of your apps or in-app purchases.

01:12:39.080 --> 01:12:42.440
And the great thing about the
App Store being on the agency

01:12:42.440 --> 01:12:45.920
model means that you can change
your pricing at any time.

01:12:45.950 --> 01:12:49.080
These new tiers also
map to existing apps.

01:12:49.100 --> 01:12:53.010
So one thing to note is that we
only support the selection of

01:12:53.050 --> 01:12:55.650
these tiers through iTunes Connect.

01:12:55.650 --> 01:13:00.620
We don't support the assignment of
these tiers through any other delivery

01:13:00.620 --> 01:13:05.500
method such as the import from file
functionality in Application Loader

01:13:05.500 --> 01:13:07.980
or the XML feed with Transporter.

01:13:07.980 --> 01:13:11.940
But I do want to point out where you can
select these tiers in iTunes Connect.

01:13:11.940 --> 01:13:14.480
This is the rights and
pricing page of the app.

01:13:14.580 --> 01:13:17.520
And you can see that the
alternate tiers are listed down

01:13:17.520 --> 01:13:19.070
at the bottom of the price tier.

01:13:19.100 --> 01:13:20.790
list.

01:13:21.370 --> 01:13:25.440
Just to illustrate what this looks like,
we'll use an example of

01:13:25.440 --> 01:13:30.200
an app priced at tier one,
which is 99 cents in the US dollar

01:13:30.710 --> 01:13:34.480
and 69 pence in the British pound.

01:13:35.060 --> 01:13:38.240
However,
if you were to select alternate tier one,

01:13:38.280 --> 01:13:41.740
the price remains 99
cents in the US dollar,

01:13:41.740 --> 01:13:45.780
but is now 99 pence in the British pound.

01:13:45.820 --> 01:13:49.940
And 99 pence is just a more
culturally relevant price point.

01:13:50.150 --> 01:13:53.220
While it might be slightly
higher for the customer,

01:13:53.230 --> 01:13:58.130
it's just another option for you to be
able to price your app competitively.

01:13:58.870 --> 01:14:01.100
And a few other examples.

01:14:01.200 --> 01:14:07.500
Tier 1 in the Euro is 89 Euro and
alternate Tier 1 is 99 Euro.

01:14:08.900 --> 01:14:14.950
And for the Chinese RMB,
6 RMB for Tier 1 and 8 RMB for Tier 2.

01:14:15.210 --> 01:14:18.200
So we encourage you to check out these
new tiers and just see what works

01:14:18.410 --> 01:14:20.900
for your app and your business model.

01:14:21.040 --> 01:14:23.900
The last feature I want to
talk about is automation.

01:14:23.900 --> 01:14:27.900
We know that your time as a
developer is very valuable.

01:14:27.900 --> 01:14:29.900
And we do all that we
can to save you time,

01:14:29.900 --> 01:14:33.900
especially when it comes to repetitive
actions with iTunes Connect.

01:14:33.900 --> 01:14:37.980
So I want to talk about two areas
of automation that I think will be

01:14:37.980 --> 01:14:40.470
very helpful with saving you time.

01:14:40.950 --> 01:14:44.260
The first area of automation
is auto-ingesting your

01:14:44.260 --> 01:14:46.680
reports from iTunes Connect.

01:14:46.710 --> 01:14:50.840
We provide you with a command line tool
that allows you to automate the delivery

01:14:50.840 --> 01:14:52.870
of your reports from iTunes Connect.

01:14:53.220 --> 01:14:55.960
This has been available for
your sales and trends reports,

01:14:56.100 --> 01:14:58.440
but we recently expanded it
to include the delivery of

01:14:58.490 --> 01:15:00.050
your payment reports as well.

01:15:00.050 --> 01:15:04.270
And it just allows you to access
your reports without actually

01:15:04.270 --> 01:15:08.480
having to log into the iTunes
Connect interface each time.

01:15:09.940 --> 01:15:13.370
In order to use this tool,
you first have to download the auto

01:15:13.370 --> 01:15:16.700
ingestion class file at the URL here.

01:15:16.730 --> 01:15:21.990
And you'll need to change your directory
level to point to the class file.

01:15:22.530 --> 01:15:24.870
And you'll also need to
create a properties file

01:15:25.000 --> 01:15:26.680
for your login credentials.

01:15:26.730 --> 01:15:32.200
That is your iTunes Connect Apple ID and
your iTunes Connect password.

01:15:32.250 --> 01:15:35.810
The great thing about this properties
file is that it just puts a little more

01:15:35.890 --> 01:15:41.060
security around your login credentials
as you used to enter this information

01:15:41.060 --> 01:15:43.040
directly into the command line.

01:15:43.160 --> 01:15:48.350
So it just allows your username and
password to be a little bit more secure.

01:15:49.050 --> 01:15:52.000
And I'll walk through what this
command line looks like for each

01:15:52.000 --> 01:15:55.780
of the reports so you know how
to do this for your own account.

01:15:56.100 --> 01:15:58.940
This is the command for the sales report.

01:15:58.950 --> 01:16:03.740
And all of the information in the
angle brackets will be your own values.

01:16:03.740 --> 01:16:07.320
And the parameters will
be delimited with a space.

01:16:07.520 --> 01:16:11.540
So you'll first start by
entering in your vendor ID.

01:16:11.590 --> 01:16:16.280
And your vendor ID is another unique
identifier for your developer account.

01:16:16.320 --> 01:16:18.750
This identifier can be
found in the Contracts,

01:16:18.750 --> 01:16:21.030
Tax, and Making module.

01:16:22.120 --> 01:16:26.440
Then you'll enter in the report type,
which is sales for the

01:16:26.440 --> 01:16:28.440
standard sales report.

01:16:28.480 --> 01:16:33.840
Or if you have any newsstand apps and
wish to download the newsstand report,

01:16:33.840 --> 01:16:36.140
you can enter newsstand.

01:16:36.510 --> 01:16:40.690
Then you'll indicate the date type,
which is the daily, weekly, monthly,

01:16:40.770 --> 01:16:42.920
or yearly interval.

01:16:43.600 --> 01:16:48.130
And the report subtype will be
summary for the standard sales report,

01:16:48.250 --> 01:16:51.710
detailed for the newsstand report,
or if you're using

01:16:51.730 --> 01:16:55.340
auto-renewable subscriptions,
you may be collecting personal

01:16:55.340 --> 01:16:59.000
information from customers who've chosen
to share this information with you,

01:16:59.000 --> 01:17:02.080
and you can download
that report using opt-in.

01:17:03.980 --> 01:17:07.990
Finally, the date range is optional,
and this is the exact date for

01:17:07.990 --> 01:17:09.860
the report you wish to download.

01:17:10.150 --> 01:17:13.180
If you don't include a date,
we'll just provide you with the

01:17:13.180 --> 01:17:15.920
latest available report based on
the parameters you've indicated.

01:17:18.150 --> 01:17:22.440
Similarly, this is the command for
the payment reports.

01:17:22.460 --> 01:17:26.560
And you'll again start by
entering in your vendor ID.

01:17:26.600 --> 01:17:29.380
But for the payment reports,
you need to include two leading

01:17:29.380 --> 01:17:32.330
zeros in front of your vendor ID.

01:17:33.070 --> 01:17:35.940
Since the payment reports
are broken out by currency,

01:17:35.950 --> 01:17:38.500
you'll then indicate a region code.

01:17:38.510 --> 01:17:43.240
And a list of the available region
codes is available in the Payments

01:17:43.240 --> 01:17:46.080
and Financial Reports User Guide in
iTunes Connect,

01:17:46.150 --> 01:17:48.290
if you need to access that.

01:17:48.540 --> 01:17:51.480
The report type is
always going to be DRR,

01:17:51.480 --> 01:17:54.980
which is the standard report
type for the payment reports.

01:17:55.030 --> 01:17:59.880
And finally, you'll enter in the fiscal
year and fiscal period.

01:17:59.880 --> 01:18:03.160
And if you need to access a
copy of Apple's fiscal calendar,

01:18:03.170 --> 01:18:06.930
there is one available in the
Payments and Financial Reports module

01:18:06.930 --> 01:18:08.220
in iTunes Connect.

01:18:10.130 --> 01:18:12.560
So that's auto-ingesting your reports.

01:18:12.600 --> 01:18:16.480
And the second area of automation
I want to cover is Apple's command

01:18:16.480 --> 01:18:19.020
line tool called Transporter.

01:18:19.140 --> 01:18:22.830
Transporter allows you to
deliver your app metadata based

01:18:22.830 --> 01:18:25.800
on our XML specifications.

01:18:26.030 --> 01:18:28.990
You can integrate Transporter
with your own content management

01:18:29.080 --> 01:18:31.380
system if you have one.

01:18:31.390 --> 01:18:34.390
And we recently introduced the
ability to deliver your rights

01:18:34.390 --> 01:18:38.260
and pricing changes through iTunes
Connect through Transporter.

01:18:38.270 --> 01:18:40.780
You can request catalog reports.

01:18:40.780 --> 01:18:44.280
And you can deliver your app
metadata through Transporter,

01:18:44.310 --> 01:18:47.940
which can be extremely helpful
when localizing your app.

01:18:47.970 --> 01:18:52.220
This brings me to the next
topic of localization setup.

01:18:52.230 --> 01:18:57.190
You've been hearing a lot about how
you should think global and be local.

01:18:57.200 --> 01:19:01.730
And Alex and Steve have talked about
how important App Store localization

01:19:01.890 --> 01:19:07.080
can be for providing your customers
with the best customer experience.

01:19:07.090 --> 01:19:09.450
We highly recommend it.

01:19:10.580 --> 01:19:15.100
We've talked about how the App Store is
available in 155 territories,

01:19:15.130 --> 01:19:20.080
and we offer you 28 languages
to set up for localization.

01:19:20.140 --> 01:19:23.900
We highly encourage you to use
professional localization resources.

01:19:23.990 --> 01:19:26.500
Alex mentioned this resource earlier.

01:19:26.540 --> 01:19:30.450
And we advise against using
automated translation services

01:19:30.470 --> 01:19:34.170
you might find on the web,
as they might translate your

01:19:34.170 --> 01:19:39.490
content but don't fully localize
it to be culturally relevant.

01:19:39.690 --> 01:19:44.940
We also encourage you to
localize anywhere possible.

01:19:45.270 --> 01:19:47.990
Alex showed a great example
of Where Is My Water?

01:19:48.060 --> 01:19:51.700
and they localized everything
including their screenshots.

01:19:51.760 --> 01:19:56.110
We know that there's a lot of fields in
iTunes Connect that you can localize,

01:19:56.390 --> 01:20:00.070
which is why the XML feed
can be very helpful.

01:20:00.940 --> 01:20:04.800
One last thing I want to talk about
regarding localization setup is that

01:20:04.800 --> 01:20:09.980
you are required to submit your app for
review when you do add new localizations.

01:20:09.980 --> 01:20:14.080
So just make sure you leave enough
time for the review process when

01:20:14.080 --> 01:20:16.470
you wish to add new localizations.

01:20:17.220 --> 01:20:19.660
And for those of you who wish
to cut down on the repetitive

01:20:19.660 --> 01:20:23.760
actions that localizing can bring,
we encourage you to adopt the

01:20:23.760 --> 01:20:26.290
automated process of the XML feed.

01:20:26.300 --> 01:20:29.960
And the steps for using the
XML feed are fairly simple.

01:20:29.960 --> 01:20:34.470
You can start by looking up your existing
metadata from the Apple database,

01:20:34.470 --> 01:20:38.800
which will provide you with your
current app metadata in the exact

01:20:38.800 --> 01:20:41.550
format that it'll need to be uploaded.

01:20:42.200 --> 01:20:45.600
From there, you can make any edits
that you wish to make.

01:20:45.640 --> 01:20:50.180
And once you've made your changes,
you can run Transporter in verify mode,

01:20:50.180 --> 01:20:54.530
which allows you to check your changes
against our XML specifications.

01:20:54.540 --> 01:20:59.300
Then, you can upload your information
so that it's ready to submit

01:20:59.300 --> 01:21:01.170
with your next update.

01:21:02.990 --> 01:21:08.580
You will still need to create your new
app versions in iTunes Connect and you'll

01:21:08.580 --> 01:21:13.390
want to monitor your state transitions
through iTunes Connect as well.

01:21:14.000 --> 01:21:17.280
And I'm not going to go over a demo,
but I do want to point out that

01:21:17.440 --> 01:21:20.780
there are a number of resources
available to you within the Manage

01:21:20.780 --> 01:21:22.600
Your Apps module of iTunes Connect.

01:21:22.600 --> 01:21:27.690
And there's also a great session
video from this year's WWDC called

01:21:27.730 --> 01:21:30.280
What's New in iTunes Connect.

01:21:30.280 --> 01:21:33.450
They talk in a little bit more
detail about the XML feed,

01:21:33.450 --> 01:21:36.990
and they do a full end-to-end
demo of what this looks like.

01:21:37.020 --> 01:21:39.620
So if you're interested in
checking out this video,

01:21:39.650 --> 01:21:42.100
you can access it from
the developer portal.

01:21:42.770 --> 01:21:44.960
And we know that once you
set up your localizations,

01:21:44.960 --> 01:21:48.720
you like to see what it looks like
for your customer on the App Store.

01:21:48.720 --> 01:21:52.090
This is the Pages app,
and just to show you what

01:21:52.220 --> 01:21:55.780
some of this looks like,
one thing that we get a lot of

01:21:55.780 --> 01:21:59.590
questions about is the list of
languages that appears in the app

01:21:59.590 --> 01:22:02.040
information section on the app page.

01:22:02.100 --> 01:22:05.470
This list of languages is
not the languages that you've

01:22:05.470 --> 01:22:07.260
set up in iTunes Connect.

01:22:07.260 --> 01:22:11.280
This list comes from the
lproj folder in your binary,

01:22:11.540 --> 01:22:15.620
and is meant to be the list of languages
that your app is localized into

01:22:15.620 --> 01:22:17.840
once the customer has downloaded it.

01:22:19.400 --> 01:22:23.140
The languages that you've set up in
iTunes Connect will automatically

01:22:23.140 --> 01:22:28.670
be displayed on the App Store based
on the customer's OS and storefront.

01:22:28.740 --> 01:22:33.660
So all you have to do is
provide the content in iTunes

01:22:33.660 --> 01:22:37.870
Connect and the localizations
will automatically display here.

01:22:37.880 --> 01:22:40.740
And just to show you
a few other examples,

01:22:40.740 --> 01:22:47.050
you can see how your localizations
look on the store by changing your

01:22:47.050 --> 01:22:48.770
OS and you can see what it looks like.

01:22:51.850 --> 01:22:54.420
So finally,
I'd like to leave you with some tips

01:22:54.420 --> 01:22:57.190
and tricks that you can take away today.

01:22:57.300 --> 01:23:02.940
Tip number one is viewing your
App Store localizations on the device.

01:23:02.980 --> 01:23:05.640
We just saw what this
looks like on the desktop,

01:23:05.720 --> 01:23:10.920
but it can be a little bit trickier to
view your localizations on the device.

01:23:10.950 --> 01:23:14.120
And we get a lot of questions about this,
so I wanted to walk you

01:23:14.120 --> 01:23:15.990
through how you could do that.

01:23:16.330 --> 01:23:19.260
You'll start by entering
multitasking mode in order

01:23:19.260 --> 01:23:21.990
to quit out of the App Store.

01:23:22.460 --> 01:23:27.610
Then you'll go to your settings
and tap General International.

01:23:28.160 --> 01:23:30.540
Then tap Language.

01:23:30.750 --> 01:23:34.700
And from here, you can select the iOS
language that you wish to view.

01:23:35.090 --> 01:23:38.110
For this example,
I'm going to choose Chinese.

01:23:39.690 --> 01:23:43.280
So tap the language and then tap Done.

01:23:43.330 --> 01:23:46.320
From there,
you'll go back to the App Store.

01:23:46.330 --> 01:23:49.620
And if you're logged into
your personal iTunes account,

01:23:49.640 --> 01:23:52.760
you'll need to sign out.

01:23:52.770 --> 01:23:55.470
Then you'll tap the Sign In button.

01:23:56.500 --> 01:24:00.100
Here you can see that the language
has started to change to Chinese.

01:24:00.180 --> 01:24:03.490
And I don't personally speak Chinese,
but I know that the third

01:24:03.490 --> 01:24:07.720
line here indicates the option
to create a new Apple ID.

01:24:07.790 --> 01:24:09.840
And this is where the trick comes in.

01:24:09.910 --> 01:24:12.720
You don't actually have
to create a new Apple ID,

01:24:12.770 --> 01:24:15.720
but you will start
walking through the flow.

01:24:16.030 --> 01:24:19.360
So tap Create New Apple ID.

01:24:19.400 --> 01:24:23.080
And then you'll be prompted
to indicate a storefront.

01:24:23.110 --> 01:24:26.820
This is where you can select
the storefront you wish to view.

01:24:27.020 --> 01:24:27.990
So tap Store.

01:24:28.240 --> 01:24:32.210
And for this example, I'll choose China.

01:24:32.520 --> 01:24:35.130
And then at this point,
you can tap Cancel to

01:24:35.130 --> 01:24:37.450
exit out of the flow.

01:24:38.050 --> 01:24:41.840
Once you exit out of the flow,
the storefront will automatically

01:24:41.840 --> 01:24:44.780
change to the territory you've selected.

01:24:44.970 --> 01:24:48.680
So now that we have our iOS
language set to Chinese and

01:24:48.680 --> 01:24:52.680
our storefront set to China,
if we search for the Pages app,

01:24:52.740 --> 01:24:58.220
we can now see the Chinese localization
as it would appear for the customer.

01:24:59.420 --> 01:25:03.640
Tip number two is regarding
tracking your customer reviews.

01:25:03.700 --> 01:25:07.300
Alex talked about how great this can
be for your business and that your

01:25:07.300 --> 01:25:08.740
customers leave some great feedback.

01:25:08.740 --> 01:25:12.260
While you can do this on the App Store,
we also encourage you to do

01:25:12.340 --> 01:25:14.200
this through iTunes Connect.

01:25:14.200 --> 01:25:18.490
You can access this page
from the app summary page.

01:25:18.490 --> 01:25:23.330
And the great thing about tracking
your reviews through iTunes Connect is

01:25:23.330 --> 01:25:28.720
that you can easily toggle between the
different territories since your customer

01:25:28.720 --> 01:25:30.660
reviews are specific to each territory.

01:25:30.660 --> 01:25:34.660
And you can access and
subscribe to an RSS feed,

01:25:34.660 --> 01:25:38.710
which allows you to get instant feedback
when customers post new reviews.

01:25:40.780 --> 01:25:46.010
Finally, tip number three is our
advice for scheduling a sale.

01:25:47.380 --> 01:25:50.200
Since the App Store is
a global marketplace,

01:25:50.230 --> 01:25:54.580
we operate on many international
time zones across the world.

01:25:54.600 --> 01:26:01.270
And what that means is that pricing
or availability change will go live at

01:26:01.340 --> 01:26:06.720
different times in different countries
on different time zones across the world.

01:26:06.750 --> 01:26:11.020
And it's what we call a rolling
price and availability setting.

01:26:11.080 --> 01:26:15.570
Because the change begins propagating
in one area and then rolls across

01:26:15.570 --> 01:26:17.890
the globe over a period of time.

01:26:18.400 --> 01:26:21.740
So to illustrate what this looks like,
we'll take a look at a map and we'll

